k, Joyce Arditti offers an in-depth look at how incarceration affects entire families: offender parents, children, and care-givers. Through the use of exemplars, anecdotes, and reflections, Joyce Arditti puts a human face on the mass of humanity behind bars, as well as those family members who are affected by a parent’s imprisonment. In focusing on offenders as parents, a radically different social policy agenda emerges-one that calls for real reform and that responds to the collective vulnerabilities of the incarcerated and their kin.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChildren of prisonerszUnited States. 0aChildren of women prisonerszUnited States. 0aPrisonersxFamily relationshipszUnited States. 0aPrisoners' familieszUnited States. 0aWomen prisonersxFamily relationshipszUnited States. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Psychotherapy / Couples & Family.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081470512440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814705131.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814705131423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814705131/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MDPM  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MDPM  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles